  "timeframe": "30m",
  "market_context": "Bitcoin was trading near a well-defined resistance level that had been tested four times. Short-side retail traders had placed stop losses just above this resistance, creating a liquidity pool.",
  "key_observation": "Price formed a long upper wick above resistance—triggering short-stop losses—then reversed sharply downward, confirming a liquidity grab by smart money.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identified a clear resistance level at ~85,333.64 with four prior price reactions (touches) confirming its significance.",
    "Step 2: Noted that short traders likely placed stop-loss orders just above this resistance, creating a liquidity pool for smart money to target.",
    "Step 3: Observed a momentum candle with a long upper wick piercing the resistance, triggering those stops and causing a short-covering rally.",
    "Step 4: Recognized the immediate reversal after the wick, indicating smart money selling into the liquidity-induced spike.",
    "Step 5: Defined entry as the close of the candle below the resistance zone (~85,333.64), with stop loss placed just above the wick’s high.",
    "Step 6: Set target at 2:1 risk-reward ratio based on the measured move from entry to wick high."
  ],
  "outcome": "Trade entered short at candle close below resistance, stop loss above wick high, 2:1 target achieved.",
  "lessons": "Liquidity grabs occur when price briefly breaches key resistance to trigger retail stop losses, then reverses. Enter on close below the liquidity zone with stop above the wick for optimal risk/reward.",
